He was told the special story of their old clock and it's previous owner, and after seeing the clock for himself, he decided to write a tune about the fascinating coincidence that the clock stopped permanently the moment its owner died. Mr. Work returned to America and released the song that sold over a million copies of sheet music about the clock grandfather entitled "My Grandfather's Clock".

Grandfather clocks, also sometimes referred to as 'Coffin Clocks', can be found in a substantial range of styles and sizes, varying from antiques built by well-known clock makers a number of centuries earlier, to those made today.

Pendulum clocks were established by clockmakers in the mid 1600's in a quote to obtain a higher degree of time-keeping precision. By providing longer pendulums, clocks kept much better time. These long-pendulum clocks were put in tall wood cases so that they could stand upright on the floor.

Since then, Grandfather clocks have ended up being very popular items of family furniture, and have actually appeared in a big range of cases-- numerous designs of which ended up being fashionable, and after that fell out of favor as fashion tastes changed. Grandfather clocks were sometimes decorated with ornate wood carving, and often came complete with chimes, tunes, and moon-phase dials.

Clock collecting is a major passion for numerous clock enthusiasts around the globe. Today, some antique clocks from the 1600's to 1700's bring tens of countless dollars.

